the most important findings.","The u and d placements depend on unspecified 1-loop QED self-energy corrections whose explicit formulas, scheme definitions, and uncertainty propagation are omitted. — MAJOR-REVISION still stands on reproducibility grounds.","The heavy-quark Koide relation uses mixed definitions of masses (running masses at selected scales for c and b, and apparently a running top mass near 162.5 GeV rather than the more familiar pole mass), but the scheme conventions and conversion details are not fully specified. — MAJOR-REVISION still stands because the precision claim is not reproducible without fully pinned conventions.","The claim that '8 of 12 fermion masses' are represented to sub-percent residuals is methodologically inflated because some of those are not out-of-sample representations but algebraic reconstructions from the same inputs used to define the framework. — MAJOR-REVISION still stands; this directly affects the paper’s claimed compression/predictive force.","The manuscript lacks full uncertainty propagation from lattice inputs, α_s, threshold matching, and correlated mass determinations, even though many claimed residuals are at the 0.1–0.5% level. — MAJOR-REVISION still stands because omitted systematics are commensurate with the claimed level of precision."],"new_errors_noticed":["My original review may have been too diffuse: several findings are not independent and should have been grouped under a single overarching problem of unpenalized search flexibility and post hoc rationalization.","I may have underappreciated that the key test can be applied claim-by-claim rather than paper-by-paper. The heavy-quark closure as evidence may be unsupportable as presented even if the broader exploratory framework is not retraction-worthy.","I did not sufficiently distinguish between descriptive representation and evidential confirmation. Some numerical fits may remain descriptively true while losing nearly all confirmatory force once tuning and multiplicity are accounted for.","There is a fresh possibility that the manuscript’s strongest numerical closure is not merely under-motivated but effectively selected from a continuum of RG scales, which is worse than choosing among a few discrete conventions because it enlarges the search space substantially.","I may also have underweighted the need for an explicit preregistered or algorithmic assignment rule for particle-to-relation placement. Without such a rule, the geometry is closer to an interpretive overlay than a testable representational law."]}

